-19. V\u00e2rsta medie a pacien\u021bilor - 41 de ani |last=H., I. |date=18 March 2020 |website=HotNews.ro}}</ref>\n\n== Response by sector ==\n=== Economics ===\n[[File:Emergency measures COVID 19 Romania.jpg|thumb|200px|\"Please  keep your distance\" notice in a Bucharest supermarket, 28 March 2020.]]\n[[File:Carrefour Brasov shelves, Covid.jpg|thumb|200px|Flour almost sold out, Bra\u0219ov, 14 March]]  \nDuring the second week of March, the [[Bucharest Stock Exchange]] recorded losses on all five trading sessions, the main index BET collapsing with 17.6%, the steepest decline since December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zf.ro/burse-fonduri-mutuale/saptamana-de-cosmar-pentru-bursa-romaneasca-prabusire-de-17-6-inca-nu-stim-daca-socul-economic-va-dura-1-luna-2-luni-sau-mai-mult-18982027 |title=S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2na de co\u0219mar pentru bursa rom\u00e2neasc\u0103: pr\u0103bu\u0219ire de 17,6%. \"\u00cenc\u0103 nu \u0219tim dac\u0103 \u0219ocul economic va dura 1 lun\u0103, 2 luni, sau mai mult\" |last=Popescu, Liviu |date=14 March 2020 |website=Ziarul Financiar}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the [[National Bank of Romania]] announced a reference rate of 4.8242 [[Romanian leu|lei]]/[[euro]], a historical maximum for the single European currency against the leu.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://incont.stirileprotv.ro/cursuri/moneda-unica-marcheaza-un-nou-maxim-istoric-in-raport-cu-leul-c-curs-a-anuntat-bnr-pentru-euro.html |title=Moneda unic\u0103 marcheaz\u0103 un nou maxim istoric \u00een raport cu leul. Ce curs a anun\u021bat BNR pentru euro |date=16 March 2020 |website=inCont.ro}}</ref> The leu continued its depreciation, reaching a maximum of 4.8448 lei/euro on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economica.net/curs-bnr-azi-17-martie-2020-leu-euro-dolar-franc-elvetian-curs-valutar-interbancar-robor-aur_181227.html |title=A doua zi consecutiv\u0103 \u00een care leul atinge minimul istoric \u00een fa\u021ba euro. Curs BNR 17.03.2020: 4,8448 lei/euro |date=17 March 2020 |website=Economica.net}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 9, interim Prime-minister [[Ludovic Orban]] announced the closure of all schools between March 11 and 22. The measure targeted all kindergartens, primary, secondary and high schools in Romania, both public and private, according to Education Minister {{ill|Monica Anisie|ro}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romania-insider.com/romania-closes-schools-coronavirus-march-2020 |title=Update: Romania closes all schools to fight coronavirus outbreak |date=9 March 2020 |website=Romania-Insider.com}}</ref> The decision affects 3.5 million students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/bucurestenii-inchiderea-scolilor-coronavirus-2909216 |title=Cum se adapteaz\u0103 bucure\u0219tenii la \u00eenchiderea \u0219colilor \u0219i ce p\u0103rere au despre \u00eenmul\u021birea cazurilor de coronavirus |last=Stanciu |first=Daniel |last2=Nistor |first2=Cosmin |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea |last3=Capoeanu |first3=George}}</ref> Likewise, several universities in the major student centres suspended their courses. These include the [[University of Bucharest]], the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]], the [[Politehnica University of Bucharest]], the [[Babe\u0219-Bolyai University]], the [[West University of Timi\u0219oara]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/universitatea-bucuresti-isi-suspenda-cursurile-2908415 |title=UPDATE. Universitatea din Bucure\u0219ti \u0219i ASE \u00ee\u0219i suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 la sf\u00e2r\u0219itul lunii |last=Radu, Cristina |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediafax.ro/coronavirus/cea-mai-mare-universitate-din-tara-ubb-suspenda-cursurile-pana-in-22-martie-18959559 |title=Cea mai mare universitate din \u021bar\u0103, UBB, suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 \u00een 22 martie |last=M\u0103gr\u0103dean, Vasile |date=10 March 2020 |website=Mediafax}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pressalert.ro/2020/03/se-suspenda-cursurile-si-la-universitatea-de-vest-din-timisoara-din-cauza-coronavirus/ |title=Se suspend\u0103 cursurile \u0219i la Universitatea de Vest din Timi\u0219oara, din cauza COVID 19 |last=M\u00ee\u021b, Adriana |date=11 March 2020 |website=pressalert.ro}}</ref> Furthermore, Anisie announced that, as a measure of prevention and control of the illnesses with COVID-19 in schools, the Ministry of Education had decided to suspend all county and regional school olympiads, as well as sports competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agerpres.ro/educatie-stiinta/2020/03/09/mec-olimpiadele-scolare-judetene-si-regionale-precum-si-concursurile-sportive-suspendate--462247 |title=MEC: Olimpiadele \u015fcolare jude\u0163ene \u015fi regionale, precum \u015fi concursurile sportive - suspendate |last=AGERPRES |website=www.agerpres.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe show ''Tele\u0219coal\u0103'' (Teleschool), announced by the Ministry of Education and dedicated to the students who stay at home during the period when the schools are closed, started on [[TVR 2]] on March 16, at 9 a.m. Students can follow, from Monday to Friday, [[mathematics]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[biology]], [[history]] and [[geography]] classes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23718809 |title=TVR: Tele\u0219coala pentru elevii care stau acas\u0103 \u00eencepe pe 16 martie - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.hotnews.ro/stire/23727012 |title=Tele\u0218coala a fost LIVE VIDEO pe ecrane \u0219i pe site-ul TVR+. ORARUL complet al cursurilor din prima s\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2n\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mobile.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Anisie announced that schools would remain closed while the state of emergency was in place, at least until after the [[Easter]] holidays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/educatie/ministrul-educatiei-scolile-raman-inchise-pana-dupa-paste-cat-e-anuntata-starea-de-urgenta-1276054 |title=Ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23726531 |title=Monica Anisie, ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\nOn April 1, in response to a [[fake news]] story which had gained traction on [[social media]] and was being destributed on [[WhatsApp]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.ziare.com/scoala/ministerul-educatiei-dezminte-un-fake-news-care-circula-pe-whatsapp-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-1604511 |title=Ministerul Educatiei dezminte un fake news, care circula pe Whatsapp: Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie! Vom face denunt penal |work=Ziare.com |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romaniatv.net/scoli-inchise-pana-pe-6-aprilie-fake-news-in-mediul-online-ministerul-educatiei-precizari-de-ulti_515528.html |title=\u015eCOLI \u00ceNCHISE p\u00e2n\u0103 pe 6 aprilie, FAKE NEWS \u00een mediul online. Ministerul Educa\u0163iei, preciz\u0103ri de ultim\u0103 or\u0103 |date=2020-04-01 |website=romaniatv.net |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>, saying that students would have to return to school in less than a week, Anisie and the Ministry of Education issued an official statement condemning the spread of false information and promised to provide in the next few days the date for the re-opening of schools, as well as the national examinations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/document-fals-cu-privire-la-modificarea-structurii-anului-scolar-2019-2020-distribuit-online-reactia-ministerului-educatiei-1284871 |title=Document fals cu privire la modificarea structurii anului \u0219colar 2019-2020, distribuit online. Reac\u021bia Ministerului Educa\u021biei |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-care-circula-online-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-2936604 |title=Ministerul Educa\u0163iei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news care circul\u0103 online: \"Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie. Vom face denun\u0163 penal\" |date=2020-04-01 |website=Libertatea |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.realitatea.net/stiri/actual/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-ce-se-intampla-cu-anul-scolar_5e7fcda91773ac0fd00c0fa2 |title=Ministerul Educa\u021biei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news: Ce se \u00eent\u00e2mpl\u0103 cu anul \u0219colar |website=REALITATEA.NET |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, Anisie announced the cancellation of national exam simulations, as well as of all school competitions and olympiads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/ministrul-educatiei-despre-bacalaureat-si-evaluarea-nationala-am-parcurs-75-din-anul-scolar-nu-se-poate-sa-inghetam-anul-scolar-2944167|title=INTERVIU {{!}} Ministrul educa\u021biei, despre bacalaureat \u0219i evaluarea na\u021bional\u0103: \"Am parcurs 75% din anul \u0219colar, nu se poate s\u0103 \u00eenghe\u021b\u0103m anul \u0219colar\"|date=2020-04-07|website=Libertatea|language=ro|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The ministry of education said that the [[Romanian Baccalaureate|Baccalaureate]] and the [[:ro:Evaluarea Na\u021bional\u0103 a elevilor de clasa a VIII-a|National Evaluation]] would most likely be held in the month of July, all of the examinations excluding the second [[Academic term|semester]] [[curriculum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/reluare-cursuri-scolare-anunt-ministrul-educatiei-2944150|title=Bacalaureatul \u0219i Evaluarea Na\u021bional\u0103 s-ar putea da \u00een iulie. Ministrul Educa\u021biei, Monica Anisie: \"Examenele nu vor cuprinde materia din semestrul II\"|date=2020-04-07|website=Libertatea|language=ro|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://romania.europalibera.org/a/monica-anisie-anul-scolar/30538078.html|title=Oficial. \u0218coala se reia dup\u0103 \u00eencetarea st\u0103rii de urgen\u021b\u0103. Simul\u0103rile, anulate, evaluarea na\u021bional\u0103 \u0219i bacalaureatul, \u00een luna iulie|website=Europa Liber\u0103 Rom\u00e2nia|language=ro|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://engnews24h.com/the-national-assessment-and-the-baccalaureate-could-be-organized-in-july-the-program-will-not-cover-the-subject-during-the-second-semester/|title=The national assessment and the baccalaureate could be organized in July. The program will not cover the subject during the second semester|date=2020-04-08|website=Eng News 24h|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\nThe [[Romanian Football Federation]] and the [[Romanian Handball Federation]] decided to suspend all matches until March 31.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digisport.ro/fotbal/pandemia-de-coronavirus-a-pus-lacat-pe-fotbalul-romanesc-frf-a-suspendat-toate-meciurile-810522 |title=Pandemia de coronavirus a pus \"lac\u0103t\" pe fotbalul rom\u00e2nesc! FRF a suspendat toate meciurile |date=12 March 2020 |website=Digi Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/frh-anunta-ca-toate-competitiile-pe-plan-intern-au-fost-suspendate/ |title=FRH anun\u021b\u0103 c\u0103 toate competi\u021biile pe plan intern au fost suspendate |last=Bulgakov, Kadi |date=13 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref> The rugby match between Romania and Belgium, to be held in [[Boto\u0219ani]] on March 14, was postponed by [[Rugby Europe]].<ref name=\"ziare\" /> The [[IWF Junior World Weightlifting Championships]] in [[Bucharest]], scheduled for March 14\u201321, have been cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/o-competitie-sportiva-din-romania-anulata-din-cauza-epidemiei-de-coronavirus/ |title=O competi\u021bie sportiv\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia, anulat\u0103 din cauza epidemiei de coronavirus |last=Iona\u0219cu, Andrei |date=2 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Romania}}\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries Confirmed cases and deaths by country, territory, or conveyance] (worldometer)\n* [https://instnsp.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/5eced796595b4ee585bcdba03e30c127 Interactive map with confirmed cases, people in quarantine, isolated people, etc.] (ArcGIS)\n* [https://covid19.geo-spatial.org/dashboard/main Maps and statistics on the situation of COVID-19 pandemic in Romania] (geo-spatial.org)\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Romania|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Romania| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Romania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Romania]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Romania]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Romania]]\n", "name_user": "GX, May 1971", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFebruary 21\u2013March 2: First preventive measures", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Romania"}
{"title_page": "Charles Gretton", "text_new": "'''Charles Gretton''' was a prominent clock and [[watchmaker]] during the golden age of English [[clockmaking]].\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Gretton\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = Charles Gretton\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = Claypole, Lincolnshire, England\n| baptised           = 24 January 1647/48 Claypole, Lincolnshire, England\n| death_date         = 25 June 1731\n| death_place        = London, England\n| resting_place      = Church of St Dunstan-in-the-West, Fleet Street, London\n| occupation         = clockmaker and watchmaker\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nGretton was baptised in [[Claypole, Lincolnshire]], on 24 January 1647/48. He was possibly the third youngest of nine or ten children. His mother was Agnes (Anne), n\u00e9e Atterby, and his father was Charles, a cottager, who held pieces of land and livestock. When his father died, Charles inherited two shillings.\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Gretton signature.jpg|thumb|The signature and seal of Charles Gretton.]]\n[[File:8 day longcase clock.jpg|thumb|300px|A fine marquetry 8-day longcase clock with quarter striking movement. Circa 1690-95.]]\n[[File:Gilt double basket spring clock.jpg|thumb|300px|An exceptional gilt double basket top spring clock engraved in Spanish. The dial having a moon phase, age of the moon, day of the week with its astronomical symbol, and the date. With separate hour repeat and pull quarter repeat. Circa 1700-05.]]\n[[File:Silver pair cased watch.jpg|thumb|300px|A typical Gretton silver pair cased watch with silver champlev\u00e9 dial, signed Gretton, London. Circa 1695-97.]]\nCharles Gretton left Claypole for [[London]] at the age of 14 to [[Apprenticeship|apprentice]] under Humphrey Downing, a freeman of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths]]. Downing had his premises on [[Chancery Lane]]. This location was spared from the [[Great Fire of London]] in 1666, but in December of the same year, Downing died. It is believed that Charles continued his apprenticeship under Cordelia Downing, Humphrey\u2019s wife, and later worked as a journeyman until he was made a [https://www.clockmakers.org/about/becoming-a-freeman/ freeman] of the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]] (the 'Clockmakers' Company') on 3 June 1772.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes 3/6/1672 - MS2010/1.</ref> \n\nCharles Gretton established his first workshop on Fleet Street with John Johnson but in 1778 moved into his own premises, \u2018The Ship,\u2019 in the vicinity of [[Fleet Street]] and Fetter Lane.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. [http://www.grettonbook.com www.grettonbook.com].P.25 - 29.</ref> Gretton worked during the period which is often called \u2018The Golden Age of English Clockmaking,\u2019 when many innovations were created and the trade flourished. He took at least eight apprentices, including his nephew Charles Kemp (who became the master to Tom Tompion\u2019s nephew), John Farewell, and Joseph Antram, the latter of whom became a clockmaker to [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]]. The best known of Gretton\u2019s apprentices was [[Henry Sully]], who after completing his apprenticeship stayed with Gretton as a [[journeyman]] for four years rather than the more customary two years. Sully then moved to France, becoming quite famous in the Continent and in Great Britain. Sully is remembered for his efforts to develop a seagoing clock for determining [[longitude]] at sea.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''.P.522 - 533, 536 - 540.</ref> Charles Gretton was a prolific maker of clocks and watches for home and abroad. ''[http://www.grettonbook.com/home THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking]'' , published in 2016, lists 74 extant longcase clocks, 52 spring clocks, five [[Lantern clock|lantern clocks]] and 29 [[Watch|watches]], but more have been discovered since.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. pp. 577\u2013591.</ref> \n\nGretton made more watches than clocks, as did many of his contemporaries. Based on dating of his extant clocks and watches, it would seem that his workshop began producing watches in about 1673, followed by clocks in the mid-1670s. Gretton\u2019s peak production lasted about 25 years, from approximately 1685 until about 1710, when his output dropped significantly.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. p. 541</ref> He continued to make at least clocks until the mid-1720s, when it is believed he retired from clockmaking. However, Gretton maintained a strong relationship with the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|Clockmakers\u2019 Company]] until the very last years of his life.\n\nGretton's earliest known extant watch dates to before 1675 and is on display at the [[British Museum]], London. The watch has crystals on both front and back, the back revealing the gilt brass top plate, which includes a subsidiary seconds dial, even though this is a pre-balance spring watch. Because of its complexity, this certainly would not have been Gretton's first watch.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. pp. 419, 443\u2013447.</ref> Gretton produced [https://www.lexico.com/definition/timepiece timepieces], [[mwod:clock watch|clock watches]], alarm watches, several forms of repeating watches (i.e., which contained [[Repeater (horology)|repeaters]]), and [[polychrome]] decorated watches with [https://anordain.com/blogs/news/this-is-everything-you-need-to-know-about-enamel-dials-part-1 enamel dials] and [[porcelain]] boxes. Many of the extant watches retain their boxes and cases; some of the makers of these items can be identified.\n\nGretton clocks were always of the highest quality, comparable to those of London's best makers. His early [[Grandfather clock|longcase clocks]] were housed in walnut cases. Later, the cases had [[parquetry]] decoration, followed by floral [[marquetry]], arabesque and then seaweed marquetry, [[ebony]]-veneered cases, and [[lacquer]]-decorated cases. He returned to walnut for his late longcase clocks.\n\nMost of Gretton\u2019s longcase movements had countwheel-[[Striking clock|striking]] control, although some had rack striking and quarter striking. Many early clocks had bolt-and-shutter [[maintaining power]].\n\nGretton's spring clocks were usually in an ebony-veneered or ebonized case with little or no decoration, other than the carrying handle. Gretton was, however, an early user of gilt basket-top cases. Most clocks originally stood on ebonized pad feet. Some peak-period spring clocks could be housed in a marquetry or [[Kingwood (wood)|kingwood]] case.\n\nAlmost all spring clocks employed rack striking. Gretton was an early adopter, if not the originator, of a strike/silent mechanism. Clocks employing this mechanism, but signed by at least one other maker (Hessenius), certainly originated from Gretton's workshop.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. pp. 279\u2013281.</ref> \n\nGretton was also an early adopter of mechanisms for silent-pull timepieces, several forms of which are known. Most Gretton spring clocks after about 1685 have a pull quarter repeat mechanism; several complex forms of this have been documented.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. pp. 270\u2013278.</ref>\n\n== The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers ==\nGretton was very active in the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]]. He became a steward in 1684 and a warden in 1688, and he was elected Master of the Company in 1700.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 30 September 1700, MS2710/3.</ref>  Gretton continued his commitment to the Clockmakers\u2019 Company until his late years, when ill health likely prevented his direct participation. The Clockmakers\u2019 Company Court appointed Gretton to represent the Company as a proprietor with the [[Bank of England]] in 1714, and he held this position for several years.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 5 April 1714, MS2701/3.</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic Activities ==\nCharles Gretton became very successful in business and had the means to acquire wealth and a number of urban and rural properties. He had a keen interest in philanthropy, particularly relating to education. In 1701, he donated \u00a350 to the Clockmakers\u2019 Company to fund apprenticeships for orphaned sons of clockmakers.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 1 September 1701, MS2710/3.</ref> In 1704, the first boy started his apprenticeship with the help of this fund. The last recorded recipient was in 1842. At least 77 boys were able to enter the clockmaking trade through this programme.<ref>Atkins, Charles Edward. (1931). ''The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers Records of Gretton's Gift. The Register of Apprentices of The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London from its Incorporation in 1631 to its Tercentenary in 1931''. London: Worshipful Company of Clockmakers.</ref> <ref>Loomes, Brian. (1981). ''The Early Clockmakers of Britain''. London: N.A.G Press.</ref> Charles Gretton\u2019s will arranged a fund and the structure to establish and maintain a School for Poor Boys, in Claypole, Lincolnshire. It is believed that this school for ten boys continued until 1823, more than 90 years after Gretton\u2019s death.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''CTHROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking''. p. 63.</ref> This charity was financed by the rent on Gretton\u2019s workshop, The Ship, on Fleet Street, which was willed to his son Thomas.\n\n\u2018Gretton\u2019s Gift,\u2019 another donation to Claypole set out in his will, continued into the early 20th century.<ref>Lincolnshire Archives, Lincoln, Misc DON 1153.</ref> Gretton was a donating governor at [https://www.londonlives.org/static/Bridewell.jsp Bridewell Hospital] and [[Christ's Hospital|Christ\u2019s Hospital]]; both engaged in education and training, and both still exist as schools.\n\n== Civic Life ==\nGretton\u2019s civic appointments included being a Warden at the church of [[St Dunstan-in-the-West]]. He also was a Common Councilman for the Ward of [[Farringdon Without]], representing the [[parish]] of St Dunstan-in-the-West for many years.\n\nHe served as a tax commissioner, and at times as an adjuster, for [[Ludgate]] and for both precincts of the parish of [[St Martin, Ludgate]].\n\n== Marriages ==\nCharles Gretton and Mary (n\u00e9e Phillips) married in 1678. They had ten children, only three of whom survived into adulthood. Mary Gretton died in December 1698, as did two of the children.\n\nTheir son Phillips attended [[St Paul's School, London|St Paul\u2019s School]], London, and [[Trinity College, Cambridge|Trinity College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], attaining his [[Doctor of Divinity]] degree at the latter.<ref>Gardiner, Robert (Ed.). (1884). ''The Admission Registers of St Paul's School from 1748 to 1876''. London: George Gardiner. p. 61.</ref> Phillips became the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] in [[Springfield, Essex]], where he stayed for the rest of his life. Phillips was married in the newly completed [[St Paul's Cathedral|St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]], London, in March 1712/13.\n\nDaughter Ann married John Houghton, a glover. Charles Gretton lived the very last years of his life with Ann at the Houghton home in [[Milk Street, London|Milk Street]], London. Ann was buried in Springfield in January 1752/53, where her nephew, Phillips' son, had become the rector.\n\nLittle is known about Thomas, the youngest son. He married Elizabeth Turner, a widow. The Ship was willed to Thomas, but \u00a310 of the yearly rent funded the charities in Claypole. Thomas was also buried in Springfield.\n\nCharles Gretton married Lucy Uffman in 1700, but she must have died, because Gretton was married again in 1711, this time to Dorothea Wilson. Gretton became a widower for the third time in 1727.\n\n== Death ==\nCharles Gretton died on 25 June 1731 and was buried at St Dunstan-in-the-West, Fleet Street, on 5 July 1731. He had reserved \u00a3100 for his funeral costs and was buried \u2018in very decent manner,\u2019 according to a newspaper at the time.<ref>Daily Advertiser, 5 July 1731.</ref> Besides his beautiful clocks and watches, Charles left considerable wealth, including at least nine properties.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Additional resources ==\nEssex Archives: Springfield Parish Records.\n\nLincolnshire Archives: Claypole Parish Records (births and deaths, deeds): Charles Gretton\u2019s parents\u2019 wills and inventories, deeds, educational history.\n\nLondon Metropolitan Archives (deeds, marriage records, tax records): St Dunstan-in-the-West vestry minutes.\n\nLoomes, Brian. Several books on horology and clockmakers, including documentation on Charles Gretton.\n\nNational Archives, Kew: Charles Gretton\u2019s will.\n\nPriestley, Phillip. (2000). ''Early Watch Case Makers of England 1631\u20131720''. Columbia, PA: National Association of Watch and Clock Collectors. {{ISBN|0-9668869-1-7}}. [http://www.nawcc.org].\n\nStevens, John J. (1965). 'The Clockmaker from Claypole.' ''Lincolnshire Historian, 2''(12), 27\u201334.\n\nStevens, John J. (1962). \u2018Charles Gretton: A Brief Resume of His Life, Compiled from Original Documents.\u2019 ''Antiquarian Horology, 4''(2), 40\u201345.\n\n== External links ==\nNational Association of Watch and Clock Collectors [https://www.nawcc.org www.nawcc.org]\n\nThe Worshipful Company of Clockmakers, London, [https://www.clockmakers.org www.clockmakers.org]\n\n<br />\n\n<!-- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gretton, Charles}}\n[[Category:1731 deaths]]\n[[Category:English clockmakers]]\n[[Category:English watchmakers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from South Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:British clockmakers]]\n[[Category:British watchmakers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Gretton''' was a prominent clock and [[watchmaker]] during the golden age of English [[clockmaking]].\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Gretton\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = Charles Gretton\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = Claypole, Lincolnshire, England\n| baptised           = 24 January 1647/48 Claypole, Lincolnshire, England\n| death_date         = 25 June 1731\n| death_place        = London, England\n| resting_place      = Church of St Dunstan-in-the-West, Fleet Street, London\n| occupation         = clockmaker and watchmaker\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nGretton was baptised in [[Claypole, Lincolnshire]], on 24 January 1647/48. He was possibly the third youngest of nine or ten children. His mother was Agnes (Anne), n\u00e9e Atterby, and his father was Charles, a cottager, who held pieces of land and livestock. When his father died, Charles inherited two shillings.\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Gretton signature.jpg|thumb|The signature and seal of Charles Gretton.]]\n[[File:8 day longcase clock.jpg|thumb|300px|A fine marquetry 8-day longcase clock with quarter striking movement. Circa 1690-95.]]\n[[File:Gilt double basket spring clock.jpg|thumb|300px|An exceptional gilt double basket top spring clock engraved in Spanish. The dial having a moon phase, age of the moon, day of the week with its astronomical symbol, and the date. With separate hour repeat and pull quarter repeat. Circa 1700-05.]]\n[[File:Silver pair cased watch.jpg|thumb|300px|A typical Gretton silver pair cased watch with silver champlev\u00e9 dial, signed Gretton, London. Circa 1695-97.]]\nCharles Gretton left Claypole for [[London]] at the age of 14 to [[Apprenticeship|apprentice]] under Humphrey Downing, a freeman of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths]]. Downing had his premises on [[Chancery Lane]]. This location was spared from the [[Great Fire of London]] in 1666, but in December of the same year, Downing died. It is believed that Charles continued his apprenticeship under Cordelia Downing, Humphrey\u2019s wife, and later worked as a journeyman until he was made a [https://www.clockmakers.org/about/becoming-a-freeman/ freeman] of the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]] (the 'Clockmakers' Company') on 3 June 1772.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes 3/6/1672 - MS2010/1.</ref> \n\nCharles Gretton established his first workshop on Fleet Street with John Johnson but in 1778 moved into his own premises, \u2018The Ship,\u2019 in the vicinity of [[Fleet Street]] and Fetter Lane.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. [http://www.grettonbook.com www.grettonbook.com].P.25 - 29.</ref> Gretton worked during the period which is often called \u2018The Golden Age of English Clockmaking,\u2019 when many innovations were created and the trade flourished. He took at least eight apprentices, including his nephew Charles Kemp (who became the master to Tom Tompion\u2019s nephew), John Farewell, and Joseph Antram, the latter of whom became a clockmaker to [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]]. The best known of Gretton\u2019s apprentices was [[Henry Sully]], who after completing his apprenticeship stayed with Gretton as a [[journeyman]] for four years rather than the more customary two years. Sully then moved to France, becoming quite famous in the Continent and in Great Britain. Sully is remembered for his efforts to develop a seagoing clock for determining [[longitude]] at sea.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''.P.522 - 533, 536 - 540.</ref> Charles Gretton was a prolific maker of clocks and watches for home and abroad. ''[http://www.grettonbook.com/home Charles Gretton: Clock and Watchmaking Through The Golden Age]'', published in 2016, lists 74 extant longcase clocks, 52 spring clocks, five [[Lantern clock|lantern clocks]] and 29 [[Watch|watches]], but more have been discovered since.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. pp. 577\u2013591.</ref> \n\nGretton made more watches than clocks, as did many of his contemporaries. Based on dating of his extant clocks and watches, it would seem that his workshop began producing watches in about 1673, followed by clocks in the mid-1670s. Gretton\u2019s peak production lasted about 25 years, from approximately 1685 until about 1710, when his output dropped significantly.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. p. 541</ref> He continued to make at least clocks until the mid-1720s, when it is believed he retired from clockmaking. However, Gretton maintained a strong relationship with the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|Clockmakers\u2019 Company]] until the very last years of his life.\n\nGretton's earliest known extant watch dates to before 1675 and is on display at the [[British Museum]], London. The watch has crystals on both front and back, the back revealing the gilt brass top plate, which includes a subsidiary seconds dial, even though this is a pre-balance spring watch. Because of its complexity, this certainly would not have been Gretton's first watch.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. pp. 419, 443\u2013447.</ref> Gretton produced [https://www.lexico.com/definition/timepiece timepieces], [[mwod:clock watch|clock watches]], alarm watches, several forms of repeating watches (i.e., which contained [[Repeater (horology)|repeaters]]), and [[polychrome]] decorated watches with [https://anordain.com/blogs/news/this-is-everything-you-need-to-know-about-enamel-dials-part-1 enamel dials] and [[porcelain]] boxes. Many of the extant watches retain their boxes and cases; some of the makers of these items can be identified.\n\nGretton clocks were always of the highest quality, comparable to those of London's best makers. His early [[Grandfather clock|longcase clocks]] were housed in walnut cases. Later, the cases had [[parquetry]] decoration, followed by floral [[marquetry]], arabesque and then seaweed marquetry, [[ebony]]-veneered cases, and [[lacquer]]-decorated cases. He returned to walnut for his late longcase clocks.\n\nMost of Gretton\u2019s longcase movements had countwheel-[[Striking clock|striking]] control, although some had rack striking and quarter striking. Many early clocks had bolt-and-shutter [[maintaining power]].\n\nGretton's spring clocks were usually in an ebony-veneered or ebonized case with little or no decoration, other than the carrying handle. Gretton was, however, an early user of gilt basket-top cases. Most clocks originally stood on ebonized pad feet. Some peak-period spring clocks could be housed in a marquetry or [[Kingwood (wood)|kingwood]] case.\n\nAlmost all spring clocks employed rack striking. Gretton was an early adopter, if not the originator, of a strike/silent mechanism. Clocks employing this mechanism, but signed by at least one other maker (Hessenius), certainly originated from Gretton's workshop.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. pp. 279\u2013281.</ref> \n\nGretton was also an early adopter of mechanisms for silent-pull timepieces, several forms of which are known. Most Gretton spring clocks after about 1685 have a pull quarter repeat mechanism; several complex forms of this have been documented.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. pp. 270\u2013278.</ref>\n\n== The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers ==\nGretton was very active in the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]]. He became a steward in 1684 and a warden in 1688, and he was elected Master of the Company in 1700.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 30 September 1700, MS2710/3.</ref>  Gretton continued his commitment to the Clockmakers\u2019 Company until his late years, when ill health likely prevented his direct participation. The Clockmakers\u2019 Company Court appointed Gretton to represent the Company as a proprietor with the [[Bank of England]] in 1714, and he held this position for several years.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 5 April 1714, MS2701/3.</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic Activities ==\nCharles Gretton became very successful in business and had the means to acquire wealth and a number of urban and rural properties. He had a keen interest in philanthropy, particularly relating to education. In 1701, he donated \u00a350 to the Clockmakers\u2019 Company to fund apprenticeships for orphaned sons of clockmakers.<ref>The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers: Court Minutes, 1 September 1701, MS2710/3.</ref> In 1704, the first boy started his apprenticeship with the help of this fund. The last recorded recipient was in 1842. At least 77 boys were able to enter the clockmaking trade through this programme.<ref>Atkins, Charles Edward. (1931). ''The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers Records of Gretton's Gift. The Register of Apprentices of The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London from its Incorporation in 1631 to its Tercentenary in 1931''. London: Worshipful Company of Clockmakers.</ref> <ref>Loomes, Brian. (1981). ''The Early Clockmakers of Britain''. London: N.A.G Press.</ref> Charles Gretton\u2019s will arranged a fund and the structure to establish and maintain a School for Poor Boys, in Claypole, Lincolnshire. It is believed that this school for ten boys continued until 1823, more than 90 years after Gretton\u2019s death.<ref>Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. p. 63.</ref> This charity was financed by the rent on Gretton\u2019s workshop, The Ship, on Fleet Street, which was willed to his son Thomas.\n\n\u2018Gretton\u2019s Gift,\u2019 another donation to Claypole set out in his will, continued into the early 20th century.<ref>Lincolnshire Archives, Lincoln, Misc DON 1153.</ref> Gretton was a donating governor at [https://www.londonlives.org/static/Bridewell.jsp Bridewell Hospital] and [[Christ's Hospital|Christ\u2019s Hospital]]; both engaged in education and training, and both still exist as schools.\n\n== Civic Life ==\nGretton\u2019s civic appointments included being a Warden at the church of [[St Dunstan-in-the-West]]. He also was a Common Councilman for the Ward of [[Farringdon Without]], representing the [[parish]] of St Dunstan-in-the-West for many years.\n\nHe served as a tax commissioner, and at times as an adjuster, for [[Ludgate]] and for both precincts of the parish of [[St Martin, Ludgate]].\n\n== Marriages ==\nCharles Gretton and Mary (n\u00e9e Phillips) married in 1678. They had ten children, only three of whom survived into adulthood. Mary Gretton died in December 1698, as did two of the children.\n\nTheir son Phillips attended [[St Paul's School, London|St Paul\u2019s School]], London, and [[Trinity College, Cambridge|Trinity College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], attaining his [[Doctor of Divinity]] degree at the latter.<ref>Gardiner, Robert (Ed.). (1884). ''The Admission Registers of St Paul's School from 1748 to 1876''. London: George Gardiner. p. 61.</ref> Phillips became the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] in [[Springfield, Essex]], where he stayed for the rest of his life. Phillips was married in the newly completed [[St Paul's Cathedral|St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]], London, in March 1712/13.\n\nDaughter Ann married John Houghton, a glover. Charles Gretton lived the very last years of his life with Ann at the Houghton home in [[Milk Street, London|Milk Street]], London. Ann was buried in Springfield in January 1752/53, where her nephew, Phillips' son, had become the rector.\n\nLittle is known about Thomas, the youngest son. He married Elizabeth Turner, a widow. The Ship was willed to Thomas, but \u00a310 of the yearly rent funded the charities in Claypole. Thomas was also buried in Springfield.\n\nCharles Gretton married Lucy Uffman in 1700, but she must have died, because Gretton was married again in 1711, this time to Dorothea Wilson. Gretton became a widower for the third time in 1727.\n\n== Death ==\nCharles Gretton died on 25 June 1731 and was buried at St Dunstan-in-the-West, Fleet Street, on 5 July 1731. He had reserved \u00a3100 for his funeral costs and was buried \u2018in very decent manner,\u2019 according to a newspaper at the time.<ref>Daily Advertiser, 5 July 1731.</ref> Besides his beautiful clocks and watches, Charles left considerable wealth, including at least nine properties.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Additional resources ==\nEssex Archives: Springfield Parish Records.\n\nLincolnshire Archives: Claypole Parish Records (births and deaths, deeds): Charles Gretton\u2019s parents\u2019 wills and inventories, deeds, educational history.\n\nLondon Metropolitan Archives (deeds, marriage records, tax records): St Dunstan-in-the-West vestry minutes.\n\nLoomes, Brian. Several books on horology and clockmakers, including documentation on Charles Gretton.\n\nNational Archives, Kew: Charles Gretton\u2019s will.\n\nPriestley, Phillip. (2000). ''Early Watch Case Makers of England 1631\u20131720''. Columbia, PA: National Association of Watch and Clock Collectors. {{ISBN|0-9668869-1-7}}. [http://www.nawcc.org].\n\nStevens, John J. (1965). 'The Clockmaker from Claypole.' ''Lincolnshire Historian, 2''(12), 27\u201334.\n\nStevens, John J. (1962). \u2018Charles Gretton: A Brief Resume of His Life, Compiled from Original Documents.\u2019 ''Antiquarian Horology, 4''(2),