{"title_page": "Sierra Club Foundation", "text_new": "{{short description|Non-profit organisation in the USA}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Companies|date=January 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = Sierra Club Foundation\n|image          = tscflogo.jpg\n|size           = 100px\n|motto          = Explore, enjoy and protect the planet\n|formation      = 1960\n|headquarters   = [[San Francisco]], [[California|CA]],  [[United States|USA]]\n|leader_title   = Executive Director\n|leader_name    = Peter Martin\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.tscf.org}}\n}}\n\n'''The Sierra Club Foundation''' is an American environmental nonprofit. It is affiliated with the [[Sierra Club]]. The organization's stated mission is to \"help educate, inspire, and empower humanity to preserve the natural and human environment.\" The Sierra Club Foundation is a public [[Charitable organization|charity]] based in [[San Francisco, California]] and founded in 1960. It provides [[finance|financial]] support to the [[Sierra Club]] and other environmental organizations. The Sierra Club Foundation funds a range of [[natural environment|environmental]] projects. The organization was founded by [[John Muir]]. Members of the organization's board of directors have included [[Lynn Jurich]] and [[Mike Richter]]. The current board of directors include [[Darren Aronofsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/darren-aronofsky-joins-sierra-club-901701 |title=Darren Aronofsky Joins Sierra Club Foundation Board of Directors |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> Steven Berkenfield, Marni McKinnney, Doug Walker and Sanjay Ranchod.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/about-tscf/who-we-are/board-directors |title=Board of Directors |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |date=2018-12-09 |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=='''Target Audience'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation\u2019s primary [[Target audience|target audiences]] are individuals and institutional donors that will provide [[financial]] support and partnerships that will go towards the charitable programs of the [[Sierra Club]]. As they are a sponsor for the [[Sierra Club]], they mainly focus on outreach to existing and potential donors, that combined, will offer support to programs under the [[Sierra Club]], as well as, other [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit organizations]] that align with their [https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/about-scf/our-values/mission values and goals]. On their website, they outline all the programs they fund, as it is very diverse,\u00a0 and their [[Finance|financials]] to ensure full transparency to their donors and audience.\n\n=='''Communications'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation has multiple meaningful collaborations to continue fueling its efforts for a cleaner and greener world. They have multiple partnerships, however, some important ones are Latino Outdoors<ref>{{cite web|url=https://latinooutdoors.org/ |title=Latino Outdoors |publisher=Latino Outdoors |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n, Greenfaith<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greenfaith.org/ |title=Greenfaith |publisher=Greenfaith |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>, Building Equity and Alignment for Impact Fund<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bea4impact.org/fund |title=BEA Fund |publisher=Building Equity & Alignment for Impact |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and the Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7genfund.org/ |title=Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples, Inc. |publisher=Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples, Inc.|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>.\n\n=='''Social Media'''==\nIn general, The Sierra Club Foundation has a small presence on social media. Its parent company, The Sierra Club has a stronger, more prominent social media footprint. The Sierra Club\u2019s social media presence typically works in tandem with the foundation. The primary way of communications for their foundation is run under \u201cThe Sierra Club\u201d as opposed to the \u201cThe Sierra Club Foundation\u201d.\nThe Sierra Club Foundation itself has a small Facebook<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/theSierraClubFoundation |title=The Sierra Club Foundation FB Page |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page that hasn\u2019t been updated since 2019. The Sierra Club has a bigger Facebook<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SierraClub/ |title=Sierra Club FB Page |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page with a much larger following. They can also be found on Twitter<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SierraClub |title=Sierra Club Twitter Page |publisher=Twitter|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> and appear to not have an Instagram page. Aside from its social media presence, The Sierra Club Foundation has a contact<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/contact |title=Contact Us |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page where users can submit questions or concerns. \n\n=='''Press Releases'''==\nThe most recent press release The Sierra Club held was on April 14th, 2020. They held five different releases that are all located on their Press Releases<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/press-releases |title=Press Releases |publisher=The Sierra Club |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page. \n\n=='''Foundation News'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation posted an update on its main page<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/ |title=The Foundation For A Healthy Planet |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> with regards to the COVID-19 situation stating that \u201cno Sierra Club Foundation staff will be in the office until at least June 15, 2020\u201d, and that \u201cAll mail is currently being forwarded and donations processed, but due to remote capabilities this process may take longer than normal\u201d. The foundation also has a News and Updates<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/category/news-and-updates |title=News and Updates |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> section and a Foundation News<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/foundation-news |title=Foundation News |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> section where they post all of their updates.\n\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment|Ecology|Earth_sciences|Energy}}\n*[[Sustainability]]\n*[[Biodiversity]]\n*[[Global warming]]\n*[[Ecology]]\n*[[Ecosystem]]\n*[[Earth Science]]\n*[[Natural environment]]\n*[[Nature]]\n*[[Conservation Movement]]\n*[[Conservation ethic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nvalues and goals. <ref name=\"test\">[https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/about-scf/our-values/mission]</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sierraclubfoundation.org/ The Sierra Club Foundation] - Official website\n*[http://www.sierraclub.org/ The Sierra Club] - Official website\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Sierra_Club_Foundation&action=edit\n[[Category:Sierra Club]]\n[[Category:Conservation and environmental foundations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1960]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Non-profit organisation in the USA}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Companies|date=January 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = Sierra Club Foundation\n|image          = tscflogo.jpg\n|size           = 100px\n|motto          = Explore, enjoy and protect the planet\n|formation      = 1960\n|headquarters   = [[San Francisco]], [[California|CA]],  [[United States|USA]]\n|leader_title   = Executive Director\n|leader_name    = Peter Martin\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.tscf.org}}\n}}\n\n'''The Sierra Club Foundation''' is an American environmental nonprofit. It is affiliated with the [[Sierra Club]]. The organization's stated mission is to \"help educate, inspire, and empower humanity to preserve the natural and human environment.\" The Sierra Club Foundation is a public [[Charitable organization|charity]] based in [[San Francisco, California]] and founded in 1960. It provides [[finance|financial]] support to the [[Sierra Club]] and other environmental organizations. The Sierra Club Foundation funds a range of [[natural environment|environmental]] projects. The organization was founded by [[John Muir]]. Members of the organization's board of directors have included [[Lynn Jurich]] and [[Mike Richter]]. The current board of directors include [[Darren Aronofsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/darren-aronofsky-joins-sierra-club-901701 |title=Darren Aronofsky Joins Sierra Club Foundation Board of Directors |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> Steven Berkenfield, Marni McKinnney, Doug Walker and Sanjay Ranchod.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/about-tscf/who-we-are/board-directors |title=Board of Directors |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |date=2018-12-09 |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=='''Target Audience'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation\u2019s primary [[Target audience|target audiences]] are individuals and institutional donors that will provide [[financial]] support and partnerships that will go towards the charitable programs of the [[Sierra Club]]. As they are a sponsor for the [[Sierra Club]], they mainly focus on outreach to existing and potential donors, that combined, will offer support to programs under the [[Sierra Club]], as well as, other [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit organizations]] that align with their [https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/about-scf/our-values/mission values and goals]. On their website, they outline all the programs they fund, as it is very diverse,\u00a0 and their [[Finance|financials]] to ensure full transparency to their donors and audience.\n\n=='''Communications'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation has multiple meaningful collaborations to continue fueling its efforts for a cleaner and greener world. They have multiple partnerships, however, some important ones are Latino Outdoors<ref>{{cite web|url=https://latinooutdoors.org/ |title=Latino Outdoors |publisher=Latino Outdoors |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n, Greenfaith<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greenfaith.org/ |title=Greenfaith |publisher=Greenfaith |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>, Building Equity and Alignment for Impact Fund<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bea4impact.org/fund |title=BEA Fund |publisher=Building Equity & Alignment for Impact |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and the Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7genfund.org/ |title=Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples, Inc. |publisher=Seventh Generation Fund for Indigenous Peoples, Inc.|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>.\n\n=='''Social Media'''==\nIn general, The Sierra Club Foundation has a small presence on social media. Its parent company, The Sierra Club has a stronger, more prominent social media footprint. The Sierra Club\u2019s social media presence typically works in tandem with the foundation. The primary way of communications for their foundation is run under \u201cThe Sierra Club\u201d as opposed to the \u201cThe Sierra Club Foundation\u201d.\nThe Sierra Club Foundation itself has a small Facebook<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/theSierraClubFoundation |title=The Sierra Club Foundation FB Page |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page that hasn\u2019t been updated since 2019. The Sierra Club has a bigger Facebook<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SierraClub/ |title=Sierra Club FB Page |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page with a much larger following. They can also be found on Twitter<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SierraClub |title=Sierra Club Twitter Page |publisher=Twitter|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> and appear to not have an Instagram page. Aside from its social media presence, The Sierra Club Foundation has a contact<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/contact |title=Contact Us |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page where users can submit questions or concerns. \n\n=='''Press Releases'''==\nThe most recent press release The Sierra Club held was on April 14th, 2020. They held five different releases that are all located on their Press Releases<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/press-releases |title=Press Releases |publisher=The Sierra Club |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> page. \n\n=='''Foundation News'''==\nThe Sierra Club Foundation posted an update on its main page<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/ |title=The Foundation For A Healthy Planet |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> with regards to the COVID-19 situation stating that \u201cno Sierra Club Foundation staff will be in the office until at least June 15, 2020\u201d, and that \u201cAll mail is currently being forwarded and donations processed, but due to remote capabilities this process may take longer than normal\u201d. The foundation also has a News and Updates<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/category/news-and-updates |title=News and Updates |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> section and a Foundation News<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sierraclubfoundation.org/foundation-news |title=Foundation News |publisher=The Sierra Club Foundation |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> section where they post all of their updates.\n\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment|Ecology|Earth_sciences|Energy}}\n*[[Sustainability]]\n*[[Biodiversity]]\n*[[Global warming]]\n*[[Ecology]]\n*[[Ecosystem]]\n*[[Earth Science]]\n*[[Natural environment]]\n*[[Nature]]\n*[[Conservation Movement]]\n*[[Conservation ethic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sierraclubfoundation.org/ The Sierra Club Foundation] - Official website\n*[http://www.sierraclub.org/ The Sierra Club] - Official website\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Sierra_Club_Foundation&action=edit\n[[Category:Sierra Club]]\n[[Category:Conservation and environmental foundations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1960]]\n", "name_user": "Nikkki2332", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierra_Club_Foundation"}
{"title_page": "Shetland (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|BBC Scotland crime drama television series, 2013\u2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Shetland\n| image                = Shetland (TV series) titlecard.jpg\n| alt                  = Series title over a view of the sea and cliff\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Crime drama]]\n| based_on             = \n| creator              = [[Ann Cleeves]]\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| starring             = [[Douglas Henshall]]<br />Alison O'Donnell<br />[[Steven Robertson]]<br />Lewis Howden<br>Stewart Porter<br>Erin Armstrong<br>[[Mark Bonnar]]<br>Anne Kidd<br>[[Julie Graham]]\n| composer             = [[John Lunn]]\n| country              = [[Scotland]]\n| language             = English, Scots, [[Shetland dialect]]\n| num_series           = 5\n| num_episodes         = 26\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = Christopher Aird<br>Elaine Collins<br>Kate Bartlett\n| producer             = Sue de Beauvoir<br>Peter Gallagher<br>Eric Coulter\n| editor               = Joris Brouwers<br>Melanie Viner-Cuneo<br>David Fisher<br>Simon Starling\n| location             =\n| cinematography       = Jean-Philippe Gossart<br>Tim Palmer<br>Stijn Van der Veken\n| camera               = \n| runtime              = 60 minutes\n| network              = [[BBC One]]\n| company              = [[ITV Studios]]<br>for [[BBC Scotland]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]] \n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2013|3|10|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00vyx9h\n}}\n\n'''''Shetland''''' is a Scottish television [[crime drama]] television series, made by [[ITV Studios]] for the BBC and broadcast on [[BBC One]], that first broadcast on 10 March 2013. Initially based upon the novels of [[Ann Cleeves]], the series was brought to screen by David Kane, who has remained a principal writer through all five series.\n\nThe series stars [[Douglas Henshall]] as Jimmy P\u00e9rez, a [[detective inspector]] working for the [[Shetland]] police, Alison O'Donnell as [[detective sergeant|Detective Sergeant]] Alison \"Tosh\" Macintosh, and [[Steven Robertson]] as [[detective constable|Detective Constable]] Sandy Wilson. [[Mark Bonnar]], Lewis Howden, Erin Armstrong, [[Julie Graham]], and Anne Kidd are also credited as principal members of the cast.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe story takes place largely on the eponymous [[Shetland|Scottish archipelago]], although much of the series' filming takes place on the Scottish mainland,<ref name=\":0\" /> with only some location filming actually taking place in Shetland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visitscotland.com/blog/scotland/shetland-series-two-bbc-one/ |title=There's been a murrrder: Shetland returns to BBC One |first=Sarah |last=Clark |website=Visit Scotland |date=6 March 2014 }}</ref> Five series have been broadcast {{asof|2019|04|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Crime drama Shetland to return for fourth series |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2016/07/11/crime-drama-shetland-to-return-for-fourth-series |newspaper=Shetland Times |location=Shetland |date=11 July 2016 |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Douglas Henshall won the 2016 [[BAFTA Scotland]] award for best actor for his role as Jimmy P\u00e9rez, and the series received the award for Best TV Drama. \n\nOn December 2, 2019, BBC One announced that Shetland would return for two further series airing respectively in 2020 and 2021. Henshall is confirmed to return to his role, along with O\u2019Donnell.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-37893926 |title=Crime drama Shetland triumphs at Bafta Scotland |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=7 November 2016 |website=BBC News Scotland |publisher=BBC |access-date=14 February 2017 |quote=Actor Television \u2013 Douglas Henshall, ''Shetland''. \u2026 Television Drama \u2013 Shetland, ''ITV Studios/BBC One''. }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe first series consists of two episodes; a single two-part story based on the novel ''Red Bones '' by [[Ann Cleeves]].<ref name=\"shet1\">{{cite news |last=Griffiths |first=Rosalind |date=22 November 2012 |title=Cleeves' new BBC drama gets premiere screening at Mareel |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2012/11/22/cleeves-new-bbc-drama-gets-premiere-screening-at-mareel |newspaper=[[The Shetland Times]] |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> This series was broadcast across two nights on 10 and 11 March 2013 and was produced by Sue de Beauvoir.<ref name=\"tele\">{{cite news |last=Midgley |first=Neil |date=11 March 2013 |title=Shetland, BBC One, review |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9920728/Shetland-BBC-One-review.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, a second series was commissioned by the BBC. Series two was extended to contain six episodes. These were filmed in 2013 and screened in 2014. This series features three two-part stories based on Cleeves' novels ''Raven Black'', ''Dead Water'', and ''Blue Lightning''. This series was produced by Peter Gallagher.<ref name=digitalspy1>{{cite web|last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a470128/shetland-gets-full-six-part-series-on-bbc-one.html |title='Shetland' gets full six-part series on BBC One |publisher=Digital Spy |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nFilming began in April 2015 for a third series, which began screening in January 2016.<ref name=shetlandtimes>{{cite news |first=Rosalind |last=Griffiths |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2015/04/09/street-closed-for-television-crime-series-filming|title=Street closed for television crime series filming |newspaper=The Shetland Times |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> This series saw a change in format; with all six episodes covering a single story, written exclusively for television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anncleeves.com/shetland/index.html|title=Shetland Stories |website=Ann Cleeves |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>  This was the first series not to adapt any of Cleeves' novels.<ref name=shetlandtimes/> [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] and [[Anna Chancellor]] were among the new cast members for this series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/what-s-on/tv-radio/game-of-thrones-star-to-join-new-series-of-shetland-1-3742074|title=Game Of Thrones star to join new series of Shetland |newspaper=The Scotsman |publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd. |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> A fourth series was announced by the BBC in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://premieredate.tv/tv-series/2825-is-shetland-coming-back-for-series-4-release-date.html|title=BBC One to Make Shetland Series 4 Soon|date=20 July 2016 |website=Premiere Date|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228131812/http://premieredate.tv/tv-series/2825-is-shetland-coming-back-for-series-4-release-date.html|archive-date=2016-02-28|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref> Again, this series is a single story played out across six episodes and written exclusively for television. [[Stephen Walters]] and [[Neve McIntosh]] were among the new cast members announced for the series. It was broadcast on BBC One beginning on 13 February 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/shetland-filming|title=Shetland \u2013 Filming underway on new series of award-winning BBC One drama|author=HM|date=30 March 2017 |website=BBC Media Centre|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Henshall confirmed that filming for series five would take place over the following four months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/shetland-doug-henshall-interview/#series-5|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|title=Doug Henshall on 'Shetland', the Series' Evolution, and Looking Back on 'Outlander'|first=Christina|last=Radish|date=6 July 2018}}</ref> Series five was broadcast on BBC1, starting on 12 February 2019.\n\nDuring the filming of the programme, the cast and crew are usually based in [[Glasgow]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/scottish-actor-douglas-henshall-perks-1738133|title=Scottish actor Douglas Henshall on the perks of filming new BBC crime drama Shetland.. in & around Glasgow|last=English|first=Paul|date=2 March 2013|access-date=2 April 2017|location=Glasgow|newspaper=Daily Record}}</ref> and other areas of mainland [[Scotland]].<ref name=shetlandtimes/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/shetland/douglas-henshall.html |title=New crime drama for BBC one starring Douglas Henshall |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014|website=BBC Media Centre |publisher=BBC |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Filming often takes place in areas with landscape or buildings reminiscent of those in the Shetland Islands, such as [[Kilbarchan]] in Renfrewshire, [[Barrhead]], where Henshall was born and grew up,<ref>{{cite news |last=Beacom |first=Brian |date=21 March 2016 |title=Interview with Douglas Henshall, star of new film Iona |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14371102.Interview_with_Douglas_Henshall__star_of_new_film_Iona/ |newspaper=Herald Scotland |location=Glasgow |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> [[Ayr]] and [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]]. \"My character\u2019s house is actually in Kilbarchan, the interior of a couple of crofts are here (in Irvine, Ayrshire) and the police station is in Barrhead\", Henshall said in a 2019 interview.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/where-is-shetland-filmed-find-out-more-about-the-detective-dramas-location-11364250160835 |work=TV BT|title=Where is Shetland filmed? Find out more about the detective drama's location|date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nFilming locations on or near Shetland have included [[Lerwick]], the main port of the Shetland Islands and on the NorthLink ferry approaching Lerwick as well as the village of [[Quarff|Wester Quarff]] south of Lerwick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/where-is-shetland-filmed-find-out-more-about-the-detective-dramas-location-11364250160835work=TV BT|title=Where is Shetland filmed? Find out more about the detective drama's location|date=5 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Rampton |title=Actor Douglas Henshall returns for a third series of Shetland  |date=9 January 2016 |url=http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/632397/Actor-Douglas-Henshall-third-series-BBC-Shetland |newspaper= [[Daily Express]] |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Some filming was done on Fair Isle for series 2 while the Hillswick wildlife sanctuary was featured in series 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/shetland-filming-locations-bbc-tv-series-5-where-filmed-islands-facts/ |work=i News|title=Shetland filming locations: where BBC series is filmed, and all you need to know about the islands |date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main cast===\n[[File:DouglasHenshall&AnnCleeves2017.jpg|thumb|Douglas Henshall (Jimmy Perez) and Ann Cleeves (author) at Bloody Scotland International Crime Writing Festival, 2017]]\n* [[Douglas Henshall]] as Jimmy Perez, [[detective inspector]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Alison O'Donnell (actress)|Alison O'Donnell]] as Alison \"Tosh\" MacIntosh, [[detective sergeant]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Steven Robertson]] as Sandy Wilson, [[detective constable]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Mark Bonnar]] as Duncan Hunter, Cassie's biological father (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Julie Graham]] as Rhona Kelly, [[procurator fiscal]] (series 2\u2013)\n* [[Lewis Howden]] as Billy McCabe, [[police sergeant]] (series 4\u2013, recurring series 1, 3)\n* [[Erin Armstrong]] as Cassie Perez, Jimmy's stepdaughter (series 4\u2013, recurring series 1\u20133)\n* [[Anne Kidd]] as Cora McLean, [[forensic pathologist]] (series 5\u2013, recurring series 2\u20134)\n* Stewart Porter as Billy McBride, police sergeant (recurring series 2; temporarily replacing Lewis Howden)\n\n===Series 1===\n*[[Sandra Voe]] as Mima Wilson\n*Claire Rafferty as Anna Haldane\n*Jim Sturgeon as Ronald Haldane\n*[[Gemma Chan]] as Hattie James\n*Geraldine Alexander as Gwen James\n*Lindy Whiteford as Jackie Haldane\n*[[James Greene (Northern Irish actor)|James Greene]] as Andrew Haldane\n*Martin Wenner as Professor Paul Berglund\n*[[Alexander Morton]] as Joseph Wilson\n*[[Sophie Rundle]] as Sophie\n*[[Sooz Aitken]] as Young Mima Wilson\n\n===Series 2===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''''Raven Black'''''\n*[[Rebecca Benson]] as Sally Henry\n*[[Brian Cox (actor)|Brian Cox]] as Magnus Bain\n*Sophia Carr-Gomm as Catherine Ross\n*[[Chris Reilly]] as Alan Isbister\n*Cara Kelly as Margaret Henry\n*[[Frances Grey (actress)|Frances Grey]] as Jess Collins\n*Freya Monk as Kitty Collins\n*Matthew Zajac as Alex Henry\n*[[Anthony Flanagan]] as Euan Ross\n*[[Tunji Kasim]] as Hugo Scott\n*Jana Reinermann as Gret Bruce\n*Jordan Young as Brian Bruce\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n'''''Dead Water'''''\n*[[Nina Sosanya]] as Willow Reeves\n*[[Alex Norton]] as Cameron Watt\n*[[David Hayman]] as Joe Dalhousie\n*[[Kari Corbett]] as Evie Watt\n*Marnie Baxter as Jenny Belshaw\n*[[Iain Robertson]] as Jerry Markham\n*[[Clive Russell]] as Adam Markham\n*[[Gerda Stevenson]] as Maria Markham\n*Neil McKinven as Andy Belshaw\n*[[Forbes Masson]] as Reg Gilbert\n*Henry Pettigrew as Iain Redford\n*[[Steven Cree]] as John Henderson\n{{col-break}}\n\n'''''Blue Lightning'''''\n*[[John Lynch (actor)|John Lynch]] as Frank Blake\n*[[Bill Paterson (actor)|Bill Paterson]] as James Perez\n