%20FILM/TELEVISION|title=British Academy Scotland Awards: Winners in 2016|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|[[BAFTA Scotland]]\n|Best Writer - Film/Television\n|[[Gaby Chiappe]]\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=2396135|title=Shetland}}\n*{{tv.com show|shetland|Shetland}}\n*{{epguides|Shetland|title=Shetland}}\n*[http://drama.uktv.co.uk/shows/shetland ''Shetland''] at [[Drama (British TV channel)|Drama]]\n\n[[Category:2013 Scottish television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British police procedural television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British workplace drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British police procedural television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British workplace drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:BBC crime drama television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC mystery television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC Scotland television programmes]]\n[[Category:British detective television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Media in Shetland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|BBC Scotland crime drama television series, 2013\u2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Shetland\n| image                = Shetland (TV series) titlecard.jpg\n| alt                  = Series title over a view of the sea and cliff\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Crime drama]]\n| based_on             = \n| creator              = [[Ann Cleeves]]\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| starring             = [[Douglas Henshall]]<br />Alison O'Donnell<br />[[Steven Robertson]]<br />Lewis Howden<br>Stewart Porter<br>Erin Armstrong<br>[[Mark Bonnar]]<br>Anne Kidd<br>[[Julie Graham]]\n| composer             = [[John Lunn]]\n| country              = [[Scotland]]\n| language             = English, Scots, [[Shetland dialect]]\n| num_series           = 5\n| num_episodes         = 26\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = Christopher Aird<br>Elaine Collins<br>Kate Bartlett\n| producer             = Sue de Beauvoir<br>Peter Gallagher<br>Eric Coulter\n| editor               = Joris Brouwers<br>Melanie Viner-Cuneo<br>David Fisher<br>Simon Starling\n| location             =\n| cinematography       = Jean-Philippe Gossart<br>Tim Palmer<br>Stijn Van der Veken\n| camera               = \n| runtime              = 60 minutes\n| network              = [[BBC One]]\n| company              = [[ITV Studios]]<br>for [[BBC Scotland]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]] \n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2013|3|10|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00vyx9h\n}}\n\n'''''Shetland''''' is a Scottish television [[crime drama]] television series, made by [[ITV Studios]] for the BBC and broadcast on [[BBC One]], that first broadcast on 10 March 2013. Initially based upon the novels of [[Ann Cleeves]], the series was brought to screen by David Kane, who has remained a principal writer through all five series.\n\nThe series stars [[Douglas Henshall]] as Jimmy P\u00e9rez, a [[detective inspector]] working for the [[Shetland]] police, Alison O'Donnell as [[detective sergeant|Detective Sergeant]] Alison \"Tosh\" Macintosh, and [[Steven Robertson]] as [[detective constable|Detective Constable]] Sandy Wilson. [[Mark Bonnar]], Lewis Howden, Erin Armstrong, [[Julie Graham]], and Anne Kidd are also credited as principal members of the cast.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe story takes place largely on the eponymous [[Shetland|Scottish archipelago]], although much of the series' filming takes place on the Scottish mainland,<ref name=\":0\" /> with only some location filming actually taking place in Shetland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visitscotland.com/blog/scotland/shetland-series-two-bbc-one/ |title=There's been a murrrder: Shetland returns to BBC One |first=Sarah |last=Clark |website=Visit Scotland |date=6 March 2014 }}</ref> Five series have been broadcast {{asof|2019|04|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Crime drama Shetland to return for fourth series |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2016/07/11/crime-drama-shetland-to-return-for-fourth-series |newspaper=Shetland Times |location=Shetland |date=11 July 2016 |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Douglas Henshall won the 2016 [[BAFTA Scotland]] award for best actor for his role as Jimmy P\u00e9rez, and the series received the award for Best TV Drama. \n\nOn December 2, 2019, BBC One announced that Shetland would return for two further series airing respectively in 2020 and 2021. Henshall is confirmed to return to his role, along with O\u2019Donnell.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-37893926 |title=Crime drama Shetland triumphs at Bafta Scotland |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=7 November 2016 |website=BBC News Scotland |publisher=BBC |access-date=14 February 2017 |quote=Actor Television \u2013 Douglas Henshall, ''Shetland''. \u2026 Television Drama \u2013 Shetland, ''ITV Studios/BBC One''. }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe first series consists of two episodes; a single two-part story based on the novel ''Red Bones '' by [[Ann Cleeves]].<ref name=\"shet1\">{{cite news |last=Griffiths |first=Rosalind |date=22 November 2012 |title=Cleeves' new BBC drama gets premiere screening at Mareel |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2012/11/22/cleeves-new-bbc-drama-gets-premiere-screening-at-mareel |newspaper=[[The Shetland Times]] |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> This series was broadcast across two nights on 10 and 11 March 2013 and was produced by Sue de Beauvoir.<ref name=\"tele\">{{cite news |last=Midgley |first=Neil |date=11 March 2013 |title=Shetland, BBC One, review |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9920728/Shetland-BBC-One-review.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, a second series was commissioned by the BBC. Series two was extended to contain six episodes. These were filmed in 2013 and screened in 2014. This series features three two-part stories based on Cleeves' novels ''Raven Black'', ''Dead Water'', and ''Blue Lightning''. This series was produced by Peter Gallagher.<ref name=digitalspy1>{{cite web|last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a470128/shetland-gets-full-six-part-series-on-bbc-one.html |title='Shetland' gets full six-part series on BBC One |publisher=Digital Spy |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nFilming began in April 2015 for a third series, which began screening in January 2016.<ref name=shetlandtimes>{{cite news |first=Rosalind |last=Griffiths |url=http://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2015/04/09/street-closed-for-television-crime-series-filming|title=Street closed for television crime series filming |newspaper=The Shetland Times |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> This series saw a change in format; with all six episodes covering a single story, written exclusively for television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anncleeves.com/shetland/index.html|title=Shetland Stories |website=Ann Cleeves |accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>  This was the first series not to adapt any of Cleeves' novels.<ref name=shetlandtimes/> [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] and [[Anna Chancellor]] were among the new cast members for this series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/what-s-on/tv-radio/game-of-thrones-star-to-join-new-series-of-shetland-1-3742074|title=Game Of Thrones star to join new series of Shetland |newspaper=The Scotsman |publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd. |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> A fourth series was announced by the BBC in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://premieredate.tv/tv-series/2825-is-shetland-coming-back-for-series-4-release-date.html|title=BBC One to Make Shetland Series 4 Soon|date=20 July 2016 |website=Premiere Date|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228131812/http://premieredate.tv/tv-series/2825-is-shetland-coming-back-for-series-4-release-date.html|archive-date=2016-02-28|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref> Again, this series is a single story played out across six episodes and written exclusively for television. [[Stephen Walters]] and [[Neve McIntosh]] were among the new cast members announced for the series. It was broadcast on BBC One beginning on 13 February 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/shetland-filming|title=Shetland \u2013 Filming underway on new series of award-winning BBC One drama|author=HM|date=30 March 2017 |website=BBC Media Centre|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Henshall confirmed that filming for series five would take place over the following four months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/shetland-doug-henshall-interview/#series-5|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|title=Doug Henshall on 'Shetland', the Series' Evolution, and Looking Back on 'Outlander'|first=Christina|last=Radish|date=6 July 2018}}</ref> Series five was broadcast on BBC1, starting on 12 February 2019.\n\nDuring the filming of the programme, the cast and crew are usually based in [[Glasgow]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/scottish-actor-douglas-henshall-perks-1738133|title=Scottish actor Douglas Henshall on the perks of filming new BBC crime drama Shetland.. in & around Glasgow|last=English|first=Paul|date=2 March 2013|access-date=2 April 2017|location=Glasgow|newspaper=Daily Record}}</ref> and other areas of mainland [[Scotland]].<ref name=shetlandtimes/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/shetland/douglas-henshall.html |title=New crime drama for BBC one starring Douglas Henshall |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014|website=BBC Media Centre |publisher=BBC |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Filming often takes place in areas with landscape or buildings reminiscent of those in the Shetland Islands, such as [[Kilbarchan]] in Renfrewshire, [[Barrhead]], where Henshall was born and grew up,<ref>{{cite news |last=Beacom |first=Brian |date=21 March 2016 |title=Interview with Douglas Henshall, star of new film Iona |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14371102.Interview_with_Douglas_Henshall__star_of_new_film_Iona/ |newspaper=Herald Scotland |location=Glasgow |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> [[Ayr]] and [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]]. \"My character\u2019s house is actually in Kilbarchan, the interior of a couple of crofts are here (in Irvine, Ayrshire) and the police station is in Barrhead\", Henshall said in a 2019 interview.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/where-is-shetland-filmed-find-out-more-about-the-detective-dramas-location-11364250160835 |work=TV BT|title=Where is Shetland filmed? Find out more about the detective drama's location|date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nFilming locations on or near Shetland have included [[Lerwick]], the main port of the Shetland Islands and on the NorthLink ferry approaching Lerwick as well as the village of [[Quarff|Wester Quarff]] south of Lerwick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/where-is-shetland-filmed-find-out-more-about-the-detective-dramas-location-11364250160835work=TV BT|title=Where is Shetland filmed? Find out more about the detective drama's location|date=5 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Rampton |title=Actor Douglas Henshall returns for a third series of Shetland  |date=9 January 2016 |url=http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/632397/Actor-Douglas-Henshall-third-series-BBC-Shetland |newspaper= [[Daily Express]] |access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> Some filming was done on Fair Isle for series 2 while the Hillswick wildlife sanctuary was featured in series 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/shetland-filming-locations-bbc-tv-series-5-where-filmed-islands-facts/ |work=i News|title=Shetland filming locations: where BBC series is filmed, and all you need to know about the islands |date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main cast===\n[[File:DouglasHenshall&AnnCleeves2017.jpg|thumb|Douglas Henshall (Jimmy Perez) and Ann Cleeves (author) at Bloody Scotland International Crime Writing Festival, 2017]]\n* [[Douglas Henshall]] as Jimmy Perez, [[detective inspector]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Alison O'Donnell (actress)|Alison O'Donnell]] as Alison \"Tosh\" MacIntosh, [[detective sergeant]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Steven Robertson]] as Sandy Wilson, [[detective constable]] (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Mark Bonnar]] as Duncan Hunter, Cassie's biological father (series 1\u2013)\n* [[Julie Graham]] as Rhona Kelly, [[procurator fiscal]] (series 2\u2013)\n* [[Lewis Howden]] as Billy McCabe, [[police sergeant]] (series 4\u2013, recurring series 1, 3)\n* [[Erin Armstrong]] as Cassie Perez, Jimmy's stepdaughter (series 4\u2013, recurring series 1\u20133)\n* [[Anne Kidd]] as Cora McLean, [[forensic pathologist]] (series 5\u2013, recurring series 2\u20134)\n* Stewart Porter as Billy McBride, police sergeant (recurring series 2; temporarily replacing Lewis Howden)\n\n===Series 1===\n*[[Sandra Voe]] as Mima Wilson\n*Claire Rafferty as Anna Haldane\n*Jim Sturgeon as Ronald Haldane\n*[[Gemma Chan]] as Hattie James\n*Geraldine Alexander as Gwen James\n*Lindy Whiteford as Jackie Haldane\n*[[James Greene (Northern Irish actor)|James Greene]] as Andrew Haldane\n*Martin Wenner as Professor Paul Berglund\n*[[Alexander Morton]] as Joseph Wilson\n*[[Sophie Rundle]] as Sophie\n*[[Sooz Aitken]] as Young Mima Wilson\n\n===Series 2===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''''Raven Black'''''\n*[[Rebecca Benson]] as Sally Henry\n*[[Brian Cox (actor)|Brian Cox]] as Magnus Bain\n*Sophia Carr-Gomm as Catherine Ross\n*[[Chris Reilly]] as Alan Isbister\n*Cara Kelly as Margaret Henry\n*[[Frances Grey (actress)|Frances Grey]] as Jess Collins\n*Freya Monk as Kitty Collins\n*Matthew Zajac as Alex Henry\n*[[Anthony Flanagan]] as Euan Ross\n*[[Tunji Kasim]] as Hugo Scott\n*Jana Reinermann as Gret Bruce\n*Jordan Young as Brian Bruce\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n'''''Dead Water'''''\n*[[Nina Sosanya]] as Willow Reeves\n*[[Alex Norton]] as Cameron Watt\n*[[David Hayman]] as Joe Dalhousie\n*[[Kari Corbett]] as Evie Watt\n*Marnie Baxter as Jenny Belshaw\n*[[Iain Robertson]] as Jerry Markham\n*[[Clive Russell]] as Adam Markham\n*[[Gerda Stevenson]] as Maria Markham\n*Neil McKinven as Andy Belshaw\n*[[Forbes Masson]] as Reg Gilbert\n*Henry Pettigrew as Iain Redford\n*[[Steven Cree]] as John Henderson\n{{col-break}}\n\n'''''Blue Lightning'''''\n*[[John Lynch (actor)|John Lynch]] as Frank Blake\n*[[Bill Paterson (actor)|Bill Paterson]] as James Perez\n*Leigh Biagi as Anna Blake\n*[[Anthony Howell (actor)|Anthony Howell]] as Peter Latimer\n*[[David Ireland (playwright)|David Ireland]] as Finlay Caulfield\n*Julie Hale as Tessa Warren\n*Keith Ramsey as Joe Blake\n*Annie Louise Ross as Mary Perez\n*Susan Vidler as Isobel Tulloch\n*Lorne MacFadyen as Angus Tulloch\n*[[Michael Nardone]] as Donnie Tulloch\n*David Annen as Bill Warren\n*Paksie Vernon as Gina Bradley\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Series 3===\n*[[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] as Michael Maguire\n*[[Saskia Reeves]] as Freya Galdie\n*[[Sara Vickers]] as Leanne Randall\n*Andrew Rothney as Robbie Morton\n*[[Archie Panjabi]] as DS Asha Israni\n*[[Anna Chancellor]] as Phyllis Brenan\n*[[James Cosmo]] as Arthur MacCall\n*Jamie Michie as Lowrie\n*Jack Greenlees as Craig Cooper\n*Kate Donnelly as Grace\n*[[Mark Cox (actor)|Mark Cox]] as Tommy Monro\n*[[Struan Rodger]] as Alec\n*[[Ace Bhatti]] as Calvin Sarwar\n*Benjamin Cawley as Edison\n\n===Series 4===\n* [[Stephen Walters]] as Thomas Malone<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://insidemediatrack.com/2017/03/shetland-series-4-begins-filming/|title=Shetland Series 4 begins filming&nbsp; \u2013 Inside Media Track|date=2017-03-30|work=Inside Media Track|access-date=2018-01-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* [[Neve McIntosh]] as Kate Kilmuir<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2018/10/shetland|title=BBC - Shetland - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Sean McGinley]] as Drew McColl<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-07-04/meet-the-cast-and-characters-of-shetland/|title=Meet the cast and characters of Shetland|work=Radio Times|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Lennox]] as Sally McColl<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Fiona Bell]] as Donna Killick\n* [[Sophie Stone]] as Jo Halley<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Gerard Miller as Alan Killick<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Allison McKenzie]] as Gail Callahan<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Julia Brown (actress)|Julia Brown]] as Molly Kilmuir<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Arnmundur Ernst Bj\u00f6rnsson as DS Lars Bleymann\n* [[Carolin Stoltz]] as DI Anke Strom\n* [[Eleanor Matsuura]] as DI Jessie Cole\n* Joi Johannsson as Andreas Hagan\n* Hannah Donaldson as Meg Hamilton<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Michael Moreland as Benny Ray\n\n===Series 5===\n* [[Rakie Ayola]] as Olivia Lennox\n* [[Derek Riddell]] as Chris Brooks\n* [[Catherine Walker (actor)|Catherine Walker]] as Alice Brooks\n* [[Tracy Wiles]] as Carla Hayes\n* Owen Whitelaw as Prentice Hayes\n* [[Lorn Macdonald]] as Jamie Hayes\n* [[Ryan Fletcher]] as Calum Dunwoody\n* John Kazek as Paul Kiernan\n* Meghan Tyler as Mags\n* Ayanda Bhebe as Daniel Ugara\n* Conor McCarry as PC Alex Grant\n* [[Robin Laing]] as Gavin Laird\n* Gail Watson as Mary Hunter\n* Frances Mayil McCann as Niki\n* Angus Miller as Donnie\n* Emma Mullen as Rosie\n* Titana Muthui as Zezi Ugara\n* Kirsty Stuart as Morag Dunwoody\n* [[Kate Dickie]] as Sam Boyd\n* [[Jenni Keenan-Green]] as Claire McGuire\n* Therese Bradley as Andrea Doyle\n* [[Robert Cavanah]] as Graeme Benson\n\n==Episodes==\n===Overview===\n{{Series overview\n| color1= #E3CD81\n| link1= #Series 1 (2013)\n| episodes1= 2\n|start1= {{Start date|2013|03|10|df=y}}\n| end1= {{End date|2013|03|11|df=y}}\n| infoA1=\n| infoB1=\n\n| color2     = #4fa8ff\n| link2      = #Series 2 (2014)\n| episodes2  = 6\n| start2     = {{Start date|2014|03|11|df=y}}\n| end2       = {{End date|2014|04|15|df=y}}\n| infoA2     = \n| infoB2     =\n\n| color3     =#6df9dd\n| link3     = #Series 3 (2016)\n| episodes3= 6\n| start3     = {{Start date|2016|01|15|df=y}}\n| end3      = {{End date|2016|03|04|df=y}}\n| infoA3     = \n| infoB3    =\n\n| color4     =#24c168\n| link4     = #Series 4 (2018)\n| episodes4= 6\n| start4     = {{Start date|2018|02|13|df=y}}\n| end4      = {{End date|2018|03|20|df=y}}\n| infoA4     = \n| infoB4    = \n\n| color5     =#96e041\n| link5     = #Series 5 (2019)\n| episodes5= 6\n| start5     = {{Start date|2019|02|12|df=y}}\n| end5      = {{End date|2019|03|19|df=y}}\n| infoA5     = \n| infoB5    = \n}}\n\n===Series 1 (2013)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Overall<br/ >No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Episode<br/ >No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Original air date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#e3cd81; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK viewers<br/>(million)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/|title=BARB \u2013 Broadcasters Audience Research Board|last=|first=|date=2017|website=BARB|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Red Bones \u2013 Part 1\n |DirectedBy      = Peter Hoar\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|03|10}}\n |Aux4            = 7.97\n |ShortSummary    = Elderly Shetlander Mima Wilson is found murdered on the archaeological site on the grounds of her croft. Detective Inspector Jimmy Perez and his team investigate, and find that somehow the murder is linked to the [[Shetland bus]].\n |LineColor       = e3cd81\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Red Bones \u2013 Part 2\n |DirectedBy      = Peter Hoar\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|03|11}}\n |Aux4            = 5.68\n |ShortSummary    = With two murders and no strong leads, Detective Inspector Perez and his team must apprehend the suspect before crowds descend on the Shetland Islands for [[Up Helly Aa]], the biggest fire festival in Europe.\n |LineColor       = e3cd81\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 2 (2014)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Overall<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Episode<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Original air date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#4fa8ff; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK viewers<br/>(million)<ref name=ratings>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&requesttimeout=500 |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board|BARB]] |title=Weekly Viewing Summary (see relevant week) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080713000000/http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&RequestTimeout=500 |archivedate=13 July 2008 }}</ref>\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Raven Black \u2013 Part 1\n |DirectedBy      = [[John McKay (director)|John McKay]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Gaby Chiappe]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|03|11}}\n |Aux4            = 6.37\n |ShortSummary    = DI Jimmy Perez and his team investigate the murder of a teenage girl whose body was found on a secluded beach, and time and again the same name crops up \u2013 that of local recluse Magnus Bain, whose home overlooks the crime scene and who had forged an unlikely friendship with the victim. But then the [[procurator fiscal]] draws attention to the unsolved disappearance of a girl named Catriona 19 years previously \u2013 a case that shares several similarities with this one.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Raven Black \u2013 Part 2\n |DirectedBy      = John McKay\n |WrittenBy       = [[Gaby Chiappe]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|03|18}}\n |Aux4            = 6.16\n |ShortSummary    = The discovery of seven-year-old Catriona's body after almost two decades prompts Jimmy Perez to take Magnus in for further questioning. But at the station, the recluse's distress leads to his attacking the inspector, and Magnus is sent for a psychological evaluation. Ploughing on, Perez re-examines the evidence, but it is only when Catriona's brother reveals she had a secret hiding place at their old home \u2013 the same house where Catherine also lived \u2013 that he finally sees a glimmer of hope.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Dead Water \u2013 Part 1\n |DirectedBy      = David Moore\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|03|25}}\n |Aux4            = 5.56\n |ShortSummary    = A journalist dies in a suspicious car accident, and when it turns out he was an old friend of Perez's, a forensic scientist is called in to ensure an objective view of the case. As the team awaits her results, they look into the reasons for the victim's return to the island and find he was chasing a lead about plans for a controversial new gas pipeline.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Dead Water \u2013 Part 2\n |DirectedBy      = David Moore\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|04|01}}\n |Aux4            = 5.53\n |ShortSummary    = The discovery of John Henderson's body leads DI Perez to wonder if this second killing is linked to the death of his journalist friend Jerry, a theory given greater weight by forensic investigator Willow Reeves' finds. But then the case takes another surprising turn with the arrival of Jerry's fiancee, carrying a memory stick he gave to her for safekeeping several weeks earlier.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Blue Lightning \u2013 Part 1\n |DirectedBy      = Stewart Svaasand\n |WrittenBy       = Richard Davidson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|04|08}}\n |Aux4            = 5.29\n |ShortSummary    = A scientist is found dead in the bird observatory on [[Fair Isle]], Perez's childhood home, so Perez and Tosh  make their way across to the island, where they are greeted by Perez's father \u2013 just before flights are grounded by incoming storms. Working alone and without a forensic team, the detectives talk to the victim's friends, family, and colleagues \u2013 and as tensions run high, the storm forces Perez and the suspects to remain together under a single roof.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = Blue Lightning \u2013 Part 2\n |DirectedBy      = Stewart Svaasand\n |WrittenBy       = Richard Davidson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|04|15}}\n |Aux4            = 5.33\n |ShortSummary    = Time is running out for Perez and Tosh as their prime suspect lies critically ill in hospital, but it's unclear whether the fire that put him there was a drunken accident or if he was the second victim of Anna's real killer. The DI turns his attention to Finlay Caulfield regarding the photos of Anna on his camera, and while it becomes clear he was obsessed with her, it may not be enough to charge the stalker with her murder. There are still so many unanswered questions \u2013 until Sandy spots something on the CCTV footage that takes the investigation in a new direction.\n |LineColor       = 4fa8ff\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 3 (2016)===\nThe broadcast of Episode 6 was delayed due to coverage of an [[FA Cup]] replay being broadcast.  In contrast to Season 2 (3, 2-part episodes), Season 3 is one 6-part story.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Overall<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Episode<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK air date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#6df9dd; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK viewers<br/>(million)<ref name=\"ratings\"/>\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Episode 1\n |DirectedBy      = [[Thaddeus O'Sullivan]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Gaby Chiappe]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|01|15}}\n |Aux4            = 6.82\n |ShortSummary    = When a young man disappears on a ferry crossing and a small boy ends up in intensive care after overdosing on Ecstasy, Perez and the team become convinced the two events are connected.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Episode 2\n |DirectedBy      = Thaddeus O'Sullivan\n |WrittenBy       = Robert Murphy\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|01|22}}\n |Aux4            = 6.02\n |ShortSummary    = Perez grows convinced that Michael Maguire is implicated in the grisly death of a young man, discovered in a shipping container.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Episode 3\n |DirectedBy      = Thaddeus O'Sullivan\n |WrittenBy       = Robert Murphy\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|02|05}}\n |Aux4            = 6.21\n |ShortSummary    = Perez and Tosh's investigation leads them to Glasgow, where they hope to uncover the truth behind Maguire's brutal death and his connection to Robbie Morton. Old ghosts return to haunt Perez, with his enemies trying to prevent him from getting to the truth.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Episode 4\n |DirectedBy      = Jan Matthys\n |WrittenBy       = [[Gaby Chiappe]] & Alexander Perrin\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|02|12}}\n |Aux4            = 6.26\n |ShortSummary    = Perez and the team are determined to track down the person who aided Michael Thompson's killer, but as the case gathers pace, the officers involved find they are all under threat. Sandy comes across the killer by chance in a ruined building, and is knocked out. Tosh, returning from Glasgow, is abducted at the airport.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Episode 5\n |DirectedBy      = Jan Matthys\n |WrittenBy       = [[Gaby Chiappe]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|02|19}}\n |Aux4            = 6.55\n |ShortSummary    = Tosh returns apparently unharmed, but the truth later comes out. Perez continues to investigate the double murder case, but finds bureaucracy getting in the way, until he tracks down a rape victim and discovers that her attacker was the son of Phyllis Brennan.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = Episode 6\n |DirectedBy      = Jan Matthys\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|03|04}}\n |Aux4            = 6.14\n |ShortSummary    = Perez and the team discover that the person responsible for the deaths of Robbie Morton and Michael Thompson is closer to home than they had thought.\n |LineColor       = 6df9dd\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 4 (2018)===\nThe broadcast of Episode 3 was delayed by 24 hours due to the broadcast of an [[FA Cup]] replay.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Overall<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Episode<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK air date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#24c168; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK viewers<br/>(million)<ref name=\"ratings\"/>\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Episode 1\n |DirectedBy      = Lee Haven Jones\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|02|13}}\n |Aux4            = 6.72\n |ShortSummary    = Perez and the team are forced to re-open a 23-year-old cold case when convicted murderer, Thomas Malone, is released from prison. The case concerns teenager Lizzie Kilmuir, who was found strangled to death on a kiln. Upon returning to Shetland, Thomas tries to make amends with Lizzie's twin sister, Kate. Meanwhile, local journalist Sally McColl attends the Shetland Folk Festival with a group of her friends, but doesn't return home later that evening. The next day, she is found strangled to death on a kiln, in what looks like a copycat of Lizzie's murder. Perez is forced to break the news to Drew, Sally's father and a former police officer who led the investigation into Lizzie's murder.\n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Episode 2\n |DirectedBy      = Lee Haven Jones\n |WrittenBy       = Louise Ironside\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|02|20}}\n |Aux4            = 6.28\n |ShortSummary    = Perez sets out to find out who attacked Thomas, and circumstances point to Benny Ray. Sandy interviews Jo Halley, who claims she saw Sally arguing with someone in Norwegian at the folk festival. Allan Killick reveals that he had realized that Sally had been lying to him when she was alive. A DNA test on a hair found on Lizzie Kilmuir's scarf reveals it is a relative of Alan. However, when Alan's deceased father is tested, it turns out they are not related. Tosh interviews employees at Forst energy, a Norwegian company that Sally had been investigating, and finds a lead from Robbie's wife, but it runs cold when she is paid off. Perez learns that Thomas's trial was unethical, partly because Benny Ray, who testified against Thomas, was a paid informant. \n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 17\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Episode 3\n |DirectedBy      = Lee Haven Jones\n |WrittenBy       = Paul Logue\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|02|28}}\n |Aux4            = 6.08\n |ShortSummary    = Tosh heads to Norway to track down the mysterious Andreas Hagan, where she meets detective Lars Bleymann, who takes an instant shine to her. Finding herself drawn into a murky world of far right campaigners, Tosh is alarmed when she returns to her hotel room later that night and finds someone going through her belongings. Perez interviews Donna after receiving the results of the DNA test.\n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 18\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Episode 4\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Gatward\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|03|06}}\n |Aux4            = 5.31\n |ShortSummary    = Perez and Tosh find themselves being pursued by the secret service as their investigation in Norway continues, but when their prime suspect, Mathias Soderland, is found shot in the head whilst bearing a sign reading \"traitor\", they are forced to return to Shetland. Perez questions Duncan about a videotape of a birthday party which Lizzie attended in the days before her death, in which he was present. Sandy receives a distress call from Jo Halley and arrives at her croft to find it has been ransacked.\n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 19\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Episode 5\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Gatward\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|03|13}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2018/11/shetland|title= Shetland episode 5|website= [[BBC]] Media Centre|access-date= 12 March 2018}}</ref>\n |Aux4            = 6.21\n |ShortSummary    = Tosh begins to question if Lars could somehow be involved in Sally's murder after picking up that he knew about roadworks that took place on the island a week before he arrived. A review of the CCTV footage of Sally arriving in Norway reveals that her keychain holds a memory stick which contains video footage of Lars attending an NDA meeting. Under scrutiny, Lars admits having assaulted Jo Halleys but denies being involved in the murders, claiming that he was witness to the argument between Sally and another man on the night of her death, but Perez is shocked when Lars identifies Duncan.\n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 20\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = Episode 6\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Gatward\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|03|20}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2018/12/shetland|title= Shetland episode 6|website= [[BBC]] Media Centre|access-date= 12 March 2018}}</ref>\n |Aux4            = 6.10\n |ShortSummary    = Jimmy realises that he has no choice but to bring Duncan in for questioning. Duncan denies murdering Lizzie and Sally, but does admit to having an affair with Donna Killick. During a review of images found on Sally's memory stick, Sandy finds a picture taken on the Unst Ferry in June 1993, shortly after Lizzie was murdered, that seemingly identifies the killer. When Duncan's DNA matches the sample found on Lizzie's scarf, Jimmy is forced to break the news to Cassie that Alan is her half-brother. After Donna confesses to the murder, Drew McColl tells Perez that he was trying to protect Donna, and that in doing so he killed his daughter, Sally. Finally cleared of both murders, Thomas suffers a fatal heart attack and dies as a free man.\n |LineColor       = 24c168\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 5 (2019)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Overall<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Episode<br />No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK air date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#96e041; color:#000; text-align:center;\"|UK viewers<br/>(million)<ref name=\"ratings\"/>\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 21\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Episode 1\n |DirectedBy      = Gordon Anderson\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|02|12}}\n |Aux4            = 7.29\n |ShortSummary    = A Shetland beach is transformed once a severed hand washes up.  When a bag containing further body parts are discovered the beach becomes a murder scene. Perez quickly determines this murder has connections to a modern slave trafficking ring. The beach victim is discovered to be Daniel Ugara who was in Shetland to find his sister Zezi, both originally from Nigeria.\n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 22\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Episode 2\n |DirectedBy      = Gordon Anderson\n |WrittenBy       = Paul Logue\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|02|19}}\n |Aux4            = 6.86\n |ShortSummary    = After the Hayes family are questioned, suspicions are raised beyond the police and the family are brutally attacked.  Perez relates Daniel's murder and his sister Zezi's disappearance to the trafficking ring. Their estranged mother Olivia Lennox becomes increasingly distraught at both her perception of pace of the investigation and her sense of guilt regarding her absence from her children's lives. She is conflicted as she left them mainly in order to protect them from dangers in Nigeria.\n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 23\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Episode 3\n |DirectedBy      = Gordon Anderson\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|02|26}}\n |Aux4            = 7.01\n |ShortSummary    = A Glasgow man, Aaron McGuire, is connected to the case; Perez, believing McGuire is a crucial figure in the gang, travels to Glasgow. Another suspect, Callum, commits suicide and, as custody officer, DC Sandy Wilson is under investigation. \n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 24\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Episode 4\n |DirectedBy      = Isabelle Sieb\n |WrittenBy       = Paul Logue\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|03|05}}\n |Aux4            = 6.65\n |ShortSummary    = Believing Zezi is still on the island, Perez and the team continue the search for her. Lennox confronts Perez, accusing him of failing her children.\n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 25\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Episode 5\n |DirectedBy      = Isabelle Sieb\n |WrittenBy       = David Kane\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|03|12}}\n |Aux4            = 6.66\n |ShortSummary    = Another trafficked victim only known as Niki turns up dead. The pressure for Perez to find Zezi becomes intense, as he believes she is at almost immediate risk. Lennox confronts the only surviving Hayes family member, Jamie.\n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Shetland (TV series)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 26\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = Episode 6\n |DirectedBy      = Isabelle Sieb\n |WrittenBy       = Paul Logue\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|03|19}}\n |Aux4            = 6.80\n |ShortSummary    = The net starts to close in around the expected location of Zezi; despite this, Lennox is suicidal. Duncan Hunter, having discovered more bodies floating in the surf, is traumatised.\n |LineColor       = 96e041\n}}\n|}\n\n==International broadcasts==\n* [[Television in Australia|Australia]]: The programme airs on [[BBC First]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=BBC First |url=http://www.bbcaustralia.com/shows/shetland }}</ref> and [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] in Australia. Series 1-3 is also available on Netflix.\n* [[Television in Belgium|Belgium]]: The programme began airing on Flemish public broadcaster [[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT]]'s main channel, [[\u00e9\u00e9n]], in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nieuwe fictie op E\u00e9n: Shetland |trans-title=New fiction on One: Shetland |website=E\u00e9n |language=Dutch |url=http://www.een.be/programmas/een/nieuwe-fictie-op-een-shetland |archive-date=3 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303143507/http://www.een.be/programmas/een/nieuwe-fictie-op-een-shetland }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Canada|Canada]]: The series is broadcast on British Columbia's [[Knowledge Network]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=British Columbia's Knowledge Network |publisher=Knowledge Network Corporation|url=https://www.knowledge.ca/program/shetland }}</ref> and streamed on Netflix.<ref>https://www.netflix.com/ca/title/80133848</ref>\n* [[Television in Denmark|Denmark]]: Danish network [[DR 1]] began showing ''Shetland'' in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland: R\u00f8dt st\u00f8v |trans-title=Shetland: Red dust |website=DR |language=Danish |url=https://www.dr.dk/tv/se/shetland/shetland-roedt-stoev?app_mode=true&platform=undefined,assetType=SpokenSubtitles,assetType=SpokenSubtitles }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Germany|Germany]]: The series began airing on [[Das Erste]] at the end of March 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mord auf Shetland |trans-title=Murder on Shetland |website=fernsehserien.de |publisher=imfernsehen GmbH & Co. KG |language=German |url=http://www.fernsehserien.de/shetland }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Ireland|Ireland]]: The series began airing on Virgin Media in February 2019\n* [[Television in Italy|Italy]]: The series began airing on [[Giallo  (TV channel)|Giallo]] in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvblog.it/post/1519799/elenco-serie-tv-2018-calendario-partenze|title=Elenco Serie Tv 2018: calendario partenze|date=11 December 2017|access-date=12 December 2017|lang=it}}</ref>\n* [[Television in Finland|Finland]]: Viewers in Finland were able to start watching the show from August 2015 on public broadcaster [[YLE]]'s main TV1 channel, where the show was titled \"{{lang|fi|Shetlandsaarten murhat}}.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetlandsaarten murhat |trans-title=Shetland Islands Murder |website=Yle TV1 |language=Finnish |url=http://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2015/08/20/shetlandsaarten-murhat }}</ref>\n* [[Television in the Netherlands|Netherlands]]: ''Shetland'' is aired as part of the \"Detectives\" series from [[KRO-NCRV]] on [[NPO 1]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Detectives |website=NPO |language=Dutch |url=http://www.npo.nl/detectives |archive-date=15 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215072553/http://www.npo.nl/detectives }}</ref>\n* [[Television in New Zealand|New Zealand]]: The programme began airing in New Zealand on [[Vibe (TV channel)|Vibe]] in January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jane |last=Clifton |date=14 January 2016 |title=TV Review: Shetland |website=Stuff |publisher=Fairfax New Zealand Limited |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/75861491/tv-review-shetland }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Norway|Norway]]: ''Shetland'' is aired on public broadcaster [[NRK]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=NRK TV |language=Norwegian |url=https://tv.nrk.no/serie/shetland }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Spain|Spain]]: The programme began airing in Galicia on [[Televisi\u00f3n de Galicia]] in October 2015.\n* [[Television in Portugal|Portugal]]: The programme began airing in Portugal on [[Fox Crime]] in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=FOX Portugal |publisher=Fox Networks Group Portugal, Lda |language=Portuguese |url=http://www.foxtv.pt/series/foxcrime/shetland }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Slovenia|Slovenia]]: The programme began airing in Slovenia on public broadcaster [[RTVSLO]] in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Napovednik |website=MMC RTV Slovenija |language=Slovenian |url=http://www.rtvslo.si/napovednik/shetlandske-skrivnosti-zakopane-skrivnosti-skotska-mini-serija-1-4-ponovitev/153750 }}</ref>\n* [[Television in Sweden|Sweden]]: Swedish public broadcaster [[SVT]] started airing the 3rd series in January 2016 on their primary network SVT1.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=SVT |publisher=Sveriges Television AB |language=Swedish |url=http://www.svt.se/shetland/ }}</ref>\n* [[Television in the United States|United States]]: The series is broadcast on many stations of the [[Public Broadcasting System]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Shetland |website=WGBH |url=http://www.wgbh.org/programs/Shetland-3236 }}</ref>\n*The series became available on [[Netflix]] in 2016. In 2018, the [[Britbox]] streaming service acquired the exclusive rights to Shetland\u2019s Series 4, releasing new episodes weekly. Similarly, Series 5 has been released one episode per week beginning April 30, 2019. <ref> {{cite web |title=The wait is finally over. Jimmy Perez is back. | website=Twitter | url=https://twitter.com/britbox_us/status/1123238287785824256?s=21}} </ref> In April 2019, Netflix dropped the series from its streaming service in the USA.  <ref> {{cite web |title=When will Season 4 & 5 of Shetland be on Netflix? | website=WhatsOnNetflix | url=https://www.whats-on-netflix.com/news/when-will-season-4-5-of-shetland-be-on-Netflix/}} </ref> [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] has Series 1-3 available for fee purchase by episode or by season but is not included in its Prime streaming subscription. (Note that Series 1 [2 episodes] and Series 2 [6 episodes] are essentially bundled into one season for purchase.)\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" \n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Royal Television Society|RTS Craft & Design Awards]]\n|Best Music - Original Title\n|John Lunn\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.televisual.com/news-detail/RTS-Craft-and-Design-Awards-the-winners_nid-3549.html|title=Televisual {{!}} NEWS & COMMENTS|last=UK|first=Televisual Media Ltd|website=www.televisual.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n|[[BAFTA Scotland]]\n|Best Actor - Television\n|Douglas Henshall\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=h